# HR Attrition Dashboard — Power BI

## Project Overview
Developed an interactive **Power BI HR Analytics Dashboard** using a dataset of **1,470 employee records**, analyzing **237 attrition cases (16.1% attrition rate)** to identify workforce trends and high-risk employee segments.

## Objective
The objective of this project is to uncover key drivers of employee attrition and provide actionable insights for HR teams to improve retention, workforce planning, and employee satisfaction.

## Dataset Summary
- Total Employees: 1,470  
- Attrition Cases: 237  
- Attrition Rate: 16.1%  
- Active Employees: 1,233  
- Features: 35 columns including age, department, job role, salary, satisfaction, and tenure  

## Key Metrics & KPIs
- Average Monthly Income: 6,503  
- Average Age: 36.9 years  
- Average Job Satisfaction: 2.73 / 4  
- Average Years at Company: ~7 years  

## Department-wise Attrition
- Research & Development: 133 attrition cases (highest)  
- Sales: 92 attrition cases  
- Human Resources: 12 attrition cases (lowest)  

## Dashboard Features
- KPI cards displaying total employees, attrition count, attrition rate, and averages
- Department and role-based attrition comparison  
- Age group and salary band analysis  
- Satisfaction-level impact on attrition  
- Clean single-page dashboard design 
- Fully interactive dynamic slicers for:
  - Department  
  - Job Role  
  - Gender  
  - Age Group  
  - Salary Band  

## Data Preparation
- Cleaned and validated 1,470 records 
- Removed inconsistencies and ensured correct data types  
- Created derived columns:
  - Age Bands  
  - Salary Bands  
  - Satisfaction Levels  

## DAX Measures Implemented
- Total Employees  
- Attrition Count  
- Attrition Rate  
- Active Employees  
- Average Salary  
- Average Satisfaction  
- Headcount Distribution  

## Key Insights
- Attrition rate stands at 16.1%, indicating moderate workforce churn  
- R&D and Sales departments contribute over 94% of total attrition
- Employees with lower job satisfaction (≤2) show significantly higher attrition  
- Mid-career employees (age ~30–40) form the largest workforce segment  
- Salary and tenure show a strong correlation with retention trends  

